Max Stirner's egoism TEMPLATE[main_articles, [[Max Stirner]] and [[Psychological egoism]]] In his The Ego and Its Own, Stirner argued that most commonly accepted social institutions - including the notion of State, property as a right, natural rights in general, and the very notion of society - were mere illusions or ghosts in the mind, saying of society that &quot;the individuals are its reality
Max Stirner's egoism TEMPLATE[main_articles, [[Max Stirner]] and [[Psychological egoism]]] Around the same time as Proudhon's most famous work was published, Max Stirner argued in The Ego and Its Own, that most commonly accepted social institutions - including the notion of State, property as a right, natural rights in general, and the very notion of society - were mere illusions or ghosts in the mind, saying of society that &quot;the individuals are its reality
